## 6.4 Emergency Handling Procedures

Effective handling of emergencies requires structured, decisive action. The controller must manage the situation while maintaining overall traffic safety.

---

### 6.4.1 Initial Response

Upon identification of an emergency, the controller shall:

- Acknowledge the aircraft immediately  
- Identify the nature of the emergency  
- Provide priority handling  
- Ensure the frequency remains clear  
- Avoid unnecessary transmissions  

The controller must remain calm and composed at all times.

Example:

GFA123, roger MAYDAY, say intentions.  

---

### 6.4.2 Prioritisation

The controller shall prioritise traffic in the following order:

1. Aircraft in distress (MAYDAY)  
2. Aircraft in urgency (PAN PAN)  
3. Other airborne traffic  
4. Departures and ground movements  

All other traffic shall be managed to avoid interference with the emergency aircraft.

---

### 6.4.3 Traffic Management

The controller shall:

- Stop departures if required  
- Issue go-arounds to arriving aircraft if necessary  
- Create separation buffers around the emergency aircraft  
- Keep adjacent airspace clear  

Where possible, simplify the traffic situation early.

---

### 6.4.4 Runway Management

The controller shall ensure:

- The runway is immediately available  
- No conflicting traffic exists  
- Vehicles or personnel are removed from the runway  
- Emergency services access is considered  

If required, the runway shall be protected exclusively for the emergency aircraft.

---

### 6.4.5 Information Provision

The controller shall provide:

- Runway in use  
- Wind direction and speed  
- Surface conditions (if relevant)  
- Traffic information (only if essential)  

Information must be concise and relevant to the situation.

---

### 6.4.6 Coordination

The controller shall coordinate with:

- Approach / Radar  
- Ground control  
- Adjacent sectors  
- Emergency services  

All coordination must be completed without delaying support to the aircraft.

---

### 6.4.7 Communication Discipline

During emergencies:

- Keep transmissions short and clear  
- Avoid unnecessary phraseology  
- Use plain language if required  
- Ensure instructions are easily understood  

The pilot must not be overloaded with information.

---

### 6.4.8 Monitoring the Situation

The controller shall:

- Continuously monitor aircraft position and performance  
- Anticipate further requirements  
- Be prepared for changes (e.g. go-around, diversion)  

Situational awareness must be maintained at all times.

---

### 6.4.9 After Landing

Once the aircraft has landed:

- Ensure the runway is vacated safely  
- Provide instructions as required  
- Coordinate emergency response on the ground  
- Protect the aircraft from other traffic  

Example:

GFA123, vacate runway when able, emergency services are on standby.

---

### 6.4.10 Documentation and Reporting

After the situation:

- Record relevant details  
- Notify supervisors if required  
- Complete any required reports  
- Review the handling for training purposes  

